# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: muzzle-loading-rifle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The **1-inch Nordenfelt gun** was an early quick-firing light gun intended to defend larger warships against the new small fast-moving torpedo boats in the late 1870s to the 1890s.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gun was an enlarged version of the successful rifle-calibre Nordenfelt hand-cranked "machine gun" designed by Helge Palmcrantz and was intended to combine its rapid rate of fire with a projectile capable of deterring attacking torpedo boats.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gun fired a solid steel bullet with hardened tip and brass jacket: under the terms of the St.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] Petersburg Declaration of 1868, exploding shells weighing less than 400 grams were not allowed to be used in warfare between the signatory nations.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gun was used in one, two and four-barrel versions.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The ammunition was fed by gravity from a hopper above the breech subdivided into separate columns for each barrel.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gunner loaded and fired the multiple barrels by moving a lever on the right side of the gun forward and backwards.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] Pulling the lever backwards extracted the fired cartridges, pushing it forward then loaded fresh cartridges into all the barrels, and the final part of the forward motion fired all the barrels, one at a time in quick succession.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] Hence the gun functioned as a type of volley gun, firing bullets in bursts, compared to the contemporary Gatling gun and the true machine guns which succeeded it such as the Maxim gun, which fired at a steady continuous rate.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gunner was occupied with manually operating the loading and firing lever, while the gun captain aimed the gun and operated the elevation and training handwheels.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The Armstrong **RBL 7-inch gun**, also known as the **110-pounder**, was a heavy caliber Armstrong gun, an early type of rifled breechloader.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] William Armstrong's innovative combination of a rifled built-up gun with breechloading had proven suitable for small cannon.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] When it was applied to a 7-inch gun, it proved that the pressure caused by the explosive charge that was required to propel a 110-pound shot was too much for his breechloading system.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The Armstrong "screw" breech mechanism used a heavy block inserted in a vertical slot in the barrel behind the chamber, with a large hollow screw behind it which was manually screwed tight against the block after loading.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] A metal cup on the front of the block, together with the pressure of the screw behind it, provided "obturation" and sealed the breech to prevent escape of gasses rearward on firing.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The sliding-block was known as the "vent-piece", as the vent tube was inserted through it to fire the gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] In modern terms it was a vertical sliding-block.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] To load the gun, the vent-piece was raised, the shell was inserted through the hollow screw and rammed home into the bore, and the powder cartridge was likewise inserted through the screw into the chamber.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The vent-piece was lowered, the screw was tightened, a tube was inserted in the top of the vent-piece, and the gun was fired.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] Shells had a thin lead coating which made them fractionally larger than the gun's bore, and which engaged with the gun's rifling grooves to impart spin to the shell.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] This spin, together with the elimination of windage as a result of the tight fit, enabled the gun to achieve greater range and accuracy than existing smoothbore muzzle-loaders with a smaller powder charge.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] On top of each powder cartridge was a "lubricator" consisting of tallow and linseed oil between two tin plates, backed by a felt wad coated with beeswax and finally by millboard.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The lubricator followed the shell down the bore, the lubricant was squeezed out between the tin plates and the wad behind it cleaned out any lead deposits left from the shell coating, leaving the bore clean for the next round.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The gun as first made weighed 72 cwt (8,064 lb) but the heavier 82 cwt (9,184 lb) version, incorporating a strengthening coil over the powder chamber, was the first to enter service in 1861.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] It was intended to replace the smoothbore muzzle-loading 68-pounder gun, and was intended to be Britain's first modern rifled breech-loading naval gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The lighter 72 cwt version eventually entered service in 1863 for land use only.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The British government's Select Committee on Ordnance held lengthy hearings in 1862 and 1863 on the relative merits of the Armstrong breechloaders compared to other breechloaders and muzzle-loaders.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] Owen, Royal Artillery, reflecting the establishment opinion in 1873.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] Critics also considered that the manual labour needed to raise the heavy (136 lb) vent piece out of the breech before reloading was an unnecessary combat impediment.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] As these limitations were imposed by the current Armstrong breechloading design, and as no other suitable breechloading mechanism was available, production of the 110-pounder was discontinued in 1864 and Britain reverted to muzzle-loading heavy guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The remaining guns were moved to the role of fortress artillery where they remained in post for much of the Victorian era.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The abandonment of the Armstrong breech-loading design led Britain to begin a major program of building rifled muzzle-loaders to equip its fleet.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The Armstrong 110-pound gun was succeeded by various RML 7 and 8-inch guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] 7-inch Armstrong breech-loaders under construction at the time of cancellation were completed as RML 64-pounder muzzle-loaders.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] However, the gun construction method developed by Armstrong for breech-loaders, of a wrought-iron "A" tube surrounded by wrought-iron coils, was considered sound and was retained for the first generation of new rifled muzzle-loaders in the mid-1860s.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] When Britain returned to breech-loaders in 1880 it used the Elswick cup and the French De Bange obturation systems, both of which used the power of the gun's firing to achieve obturation rather than manual labour.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The gun was used extensively by Royal Navy ships against land fortifications in the Bombardment of Kagoshima and Bombardment of Shimonoseki in 1863 and 1864.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] — Letter from an officer of HMS *Euryalus* to historian William Laird Clowes many years after the event.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] — An officer from HMS *Euryalus*, published in *The Times* on 25 April 1864.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] The guns, while functioning well when correctly handled, were hence seen to be difficult and potentially dangerous to use under the stress of combat.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] During the New Zealand Wars, the gun was used in the bombardment of the Maori fortifications at Gate Pa on 29 April 1864.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-pounder-breech-loader] Although subjected to one of the fiercest bombardments of the wars, the Maori defenders were protected by anti-artillery bunkers and went on to repel the British force, inflicting heavy casualties.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The **100-ton gun** (also known as the **Armstrong 100-ton gun**) was a British coastal defense gun and is the world's largest black powder cannon.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] It is a 17.72-inch (450 mm) rifled muzzle-loading (RML) gun made by Elswick Ordnance Company, the armaments division of the British manufacturing company Armstrong Whitworth, owned by William Armstrong.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The 15 guns Armstrong made were used to arm two Italian battleships and, to counter these, British fortifications at Malta and Gibraltar.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] French industries soon made a 420 mm (17 in), 76 t (75 long tons; 84 short tons) gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] This led the Royal Navy to ask for an 81 t (80 long tons; 89 short tons) gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Armstrong, the main British artillery producer, began a project for creation of an even larger weapon, an 18 in (460 mm) gun, also called the '100 ton'.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Armstrong offered it to the Royal Navy, which rejected the gun, deeming it too heavy and costly.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The 100 ton gun was enormous for its time.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The weight was comparable to that of the much later *Iowa*-class 406 mm (16.0 in)/50cal guns, even though their barrels were quite short.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] They were muzzle-loading guns, with a rifled tube and rigid mount.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Each gun required a crew of 35 men, including 18 men to handle the ammunition.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The 100-ton gun was first built with a caliber of 17 in (430 mm) throughout the whole length of its bore.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The barrel's outer diameter was 77 in (2.0 m) at the breech, which reduced to 29 in (740 mm) at the muzzle.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The length of bore was 30 feet 6 inches (9.30 m) long, or 21.5 calibers.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The rifling consisted of 27 grooves of 1/8-inch depth and had a progressive twist rate of L/45 at the muzzle.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The driving bands of the shells were attached gas-checks instead of the traditional studs.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The weight of the gun was 101.5 LT (103.1 t), or about 100 tons.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The gun was built up from an inner steel tube surrounded by multiple wrought iron coils.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The inner tube itself consisted of two parts joined by a double ring.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] This was caused by the manufacturer being unable to make this in one piece.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The loading gear of the gun was hydraulic.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] In a fixed position, the barrel was declined to bring in the charge and a ram head then forced the shot up the bore to its seat against the charge.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] After firing, the gun was again brought back to this position.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The ram, which had a sponge head, would then be brought in again.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] When it reached the back of the gun it would unleash a powerful jet of water to clean the barrel and make sure no fire was left.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Once the ram had been withdrawn, a new charge and shot were brought up in turn and positioned before the barrel.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The whole operation was handled by a man pulling levers.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Firing was mechanical or electrical, with an optical system for aiming.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The gun crews could fire a projectile once every six minutes.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Muzzle velocity was 472 m/s (1,550 ft/s) and maximum elevation was 10° 30'.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] At maximum charge 204 kg (450 lb)?) and maximum elevation, a projectile could achieve a range of only 5,990 m (19,650 ft), but at that distance the projectile could still pierce 394 mm (15.5 in) of steel (it is not clear if it was mild or hardened).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The platform was sloped at 4 degrees to slow the recoil.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] On the platform mount, hydraulic systems powered chains that traversed the guns through an arc of 150 degrees; another hydraulic system provided elevation.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] After tests in Italy, the first gun was returned to the factory to get a caliber of 17.75 in (451 mm) and a powder chamber with a diameter of 19.75 in (502 mm).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Chambering was a recent innovation and gave this gun an about 35% larger charge chamber.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] In theory, a larger chamber allowed a higher charge without raising peak pressures.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] However, as boring up the chamber reduced the gun's strength, the gun was strengthened near the front of the chamber.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] This was done while retaining the same weight.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Another innovation was the use of shallower polygonal rifling.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] All other guns were directly built to incorporate these changes.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] This was a second-generation RML gun, equipped with polygroove rifling and firing only studless ammunition with automatic gas-checks for rotation.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Firing charges were polygonal in shape, with 399 x 368 mm maximum width and length.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] They were made of 1 cwt (51 kg (112 lb)) 'Large Black Prism' propellant, and four or five were needed for every shell fired at maximum power.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The recoil was 1.75 m (5 ft 9 in) as two hydraulic pistons in the rear part of platform absorbed the remaining energy.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] After the reunification of Italy, the Regia Marina began an innovative program to field the best and most powerful battleships of the time, the first being the *Duilio*-class, armed with 380 mm guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] They were already very powerful, but in February 1874 when the UK started to build HMS *Inflexible*, armed with 406 mm (16.0 in) guns, Italian admirals called for even more powerful guns, to hold the lead in battleship design.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] On 21 July 1874, Armstrong signed a contract with Italy to deliver eight of its 100-ton guns, enough to arm *Duilio* and her sister-ship *Dandolo*.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The order of the 100-ton gun is closely linked to the construction of the Swing Bridge over the River Tyne in Newcastle upon Tyne.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] This hydraulic swing bridge was also built by Armstrong and at the time, it was the largest of the world.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] On 17 July 1876, it was opened by the Italian Navy steamer *Europa*, which came to collect the first 100-ton gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] In La Spezia, a special 160t crane had been built at the arsenal to handle the 100-ton gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] This was a steam driven hydraulic crane designed by George Wightwick Rendel, the first of Italy.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The Italian Navy tested the 100-ton gun at Muggiano near La Spezia.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Here the 100-ton gun was mounted on a 26 by 16 m iron pontoon which stuck out 1 m above the waterline.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The pontoon was docked in a basin close to shore.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Elevation and declination of the gun was done by hydraulics, powered by a steam engine.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The pontoon allowed the gun to turn in the absence of a turret.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The setup with the pontoon was inspected by George Rendel and Captain Noble, partners in the Armstrong firm.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Noble was also a known expert on gas pressures in cannon.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Younghusband of the Woolwich arsenal and Col.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Some preliminary shot were fired on 20, 22, and 23 October 1876.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] On the third day, velocity measurements finally worked.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] With a charge of 330 pounds (150 kg), a shot of 2,000 pounds (910 kg) got a velocity of 1,446 feet per second (441 m/s).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The tests against armor targets drew international attention.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The targets were indeed mock-ups of ship hulls placed on embankments in a ravine.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The first target had two 11 feet 11 inches (3.63 m) long and 4 feet 8 inches (1.42 m) wide Creusot steel plates, placed one above the other.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Each was 22 inches (56 cm) thick and backed by two layers of teak collectively 29 inches (74 cm) thick.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Behind that was an 1.5 inches (3.8 cm) iron skin and behind that, frames, representing those of a ship.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] These steel plates were reported to be of very soft steel, meaning that its ductility was supposed to keep it from fracturing.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The second target was similar in every respect.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Above, it had a wrought iron front plate by Cammell of Sheffield, below that was a wrought iron plate by Marrell.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The third target was of the same dimensions.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] However, the upper half was made up of two Cammell wrought iron plates of 12 and 10-inch, with 14-inch of timber in between.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The lower half contained a 14-inch chilled cast iron plate in the back and an 8-inch wrought iron plate in front.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The fourth target was like the third, but with plates made by Marrell and timber in between the wrought and chilled iron plates.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The total thickness of all four targets was the same at 4 feet 4 inches (1.32 m).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The raft with the 100-ton gun was about 110 m from the targets.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Other guns that participated in the test were a RML 11-inch 23-ton gun and two RML 10-inch 18-ton gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] As these were about 80 m from the target, the range of the guns was almost the same.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The smaller guns were placed so that they could be moved sideways to allow the big gun to fire.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] On 25 October, the 10-inch gun fired at the upper half of the steel target.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The shot penetrated only 10 inches (25 cm) into the first plate, but a few seconds later the plate 'began to sing' and cracks began to extend from the hole.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The Cammell and Marrell wrought iron plates resisted the 10-inch gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Later, the 10 and 11-inch guns defeated the steel target.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The day ended with the 100-ton gun firing towards the sea.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] On the 26th, it fired against the untouched Creusot plate and completely destroyed it.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] However, the shot broke up and did not get through the target.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] While experts concluded that steel was unsuitable for armor, they were puzzled by the cracks from the lighter shot.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] During the next days, the 100-ton gun fired at the iron targets.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] These plates were not reduced to pieces.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] However, the projectiles went straight through with a remaining velocity of about 600 feet per second (180 m/s) and made a very large rent in the iron plates.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] It meant that the iron vs. steel discussion was again open.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] In mid-November 1876, Nathaniel Barnsby, Director of Naval Construction to the Royal Navy was to go to La Spezia to study the results and the merits of using steel.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] A detailed overview with illustrations of these tests was published.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The 100-ton gun fired 39 shot from 20 October to 8 November 1876.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The gunpowder used for most shot was the English government Waltham Abbey gunpowder of 1.5 inch cube, although some shots were done with less offensive Fossano gunpowder.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The highest observed pressure was 20.8 ton per square inch or 3,170 atm with a charge of 330 pounds (150 kg) and a velocity of 443 m/s.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Pressures were quite irregular, with some higher charges yielding lower peak pressures.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Overall, this led the representatives of Armstrong to propose a maximum charge of 145 kg or 300 lb.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] This gave a velocity of 434 m/s, which was well above the contracted velocity of 423 m/s with a pressure of 2,800 atm.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] After the first chambered guns had been made, one of these was tested in La Spezia in March and April 1878.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] With the proper charges and a projectile of 2,000 pounds (910 kg), the original gun had given a velocity of 1,424 feet per second (434 m/s) at a pressure of 18.3 tons per square inch.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] For the chambered gun, this was 1,585 feet per second (483 m/s) at a pressure of 17 tons per square inch.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] This meant that chambering had increased the energy of the gun by about 25%.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The Fossano gunpowder also seemed very effective.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Three rounds were fired with an average charge of 433.4 pounds (196.6 kg) of English powder and 492.2 pounds (223.3 kg) of Fossano powder.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] On average, the Fossano gunpowder increased the energy of the gun by about three percent while it reduced pressure by about 4 tons per square inch.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] While the English gunpowder was best ignited in the center, the Fossano powder did not seem to suffer from ignition at the end of the charge.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] During firing trials on 5 March 1880, one of *Duilio'*s guns cracked while firing at the maximum charge.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] At the suggestion of the British Army, it was officially established that the maximum practical charge was 204 kg (450 lb) and not 255 kg (562 lb).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The Italian contract shocked British authorities, who had the Malta naval base to defend.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The opening of the Suez Canal in 1869 had rendered Malta the most important British base in the Mediterranean.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Although Malta's defenses included 320 mm (13 in) guns, this left Malta poorly defended against a possible attack from *Duilio*-class ships.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] This was a worrying problem because Francesco Crispi, one of the key architects of the Italian reunification, had called Malta "*Italia irredenta*" ("Unredeemed Italy").
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The British feared that *Duilio* and *Dandolo*, which were already well-armored, could fire on Malta's shore batteries, destroying them one after the other, while keeping outside the effective range of the batteries' guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] But the British Army's concerns had no immediate effect on London bureaucracy; until the Italians launched *Duilio* in May 1876, London made no decision.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The Royal Navy finally responded, requesting proposals from British arms manufacturers for a gun capable of piercing 36-inch steel at 1000 yd (900 mm at 900 m).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The manufacturers returned with designs for immense guns of 163, 193, and 224 tons.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] In December 1877, Simmons, chief of Malta defenses, was called to London to discuss the issue.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] He asked for four guns comparable to *Duilio's* at 3,000 yd (2,700 m).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Due to the emergency, it was decided that the fastest and simplest solution was to quit designing the bigger guns and to buy the same weapons as those on *Duilio*, because generally a shore battery with the same caliber guns as a vessel retains an advantage over the vessel.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Four guns were requested in March 1878, and manufacture started in August; in the meantime *Duilio* had been conducting sea trials since 1877.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] When Gibraltar's commanders heard of these big guns they too asked for some, which they obtained.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Two of the four guns ordered for Malta would go to Gibraltar instead.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] HMS *Stanley*, a cargo vessel specially adapted for the task, delivered Malta's two guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] One gun was placed in Cambridge Battery, which was ready in 1886, and the other in Rinella Battery, which was completed in 1884.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Cambridge received its gun on 16 September 1882, but only mounted it on 20 February 1884.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Rinella received its on 31 July 1883, and mounted it on 12 January 1884.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] By this time, the *Duilio*-class ships had been operational for around seven years.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The work to make these machines serviceable was so great that until 1885 there were no firing tests.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The first ammunition load comprised all the models available, including 50 AP and 50 HE shells.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Shrapnel, once fired, was not replaced, being considered less effective.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Between 1887 and 1888, activity stopped due to the need to rework hydraulic systems, but nevertheless the guns were considered quite reliable, serving for more than 20 years.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The careers of the guns were unspectacular, as no Italian battleship threatened Malta after their installation.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The Malta guns were phased out in 1906, as was the remaining gun at Gibraltar.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] All had fired their last shots a few years before in 1903 or 1904.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] During the First World War the guns at Malta were supposedly made ready for use when SMS *Goeben* was known to be nearby.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] *Goeben* would have had no difficulty engaging Malta's guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The first battery built for the guns in Gibraltar was Napier of Magdala, on Rosia Bay, and the second, called Victoria Battery, was placed one kilometre north.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Construction started in December 1878, with the first ready in 1883 and the second in 1884.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] HMS *Stanley* also delivered Gibraltar's two guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The first gun arrived on 19 December 1882, and the second on 14 March 1883.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] These two guns were ready on their mounts in July and September 1883.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The first firings took place in 1884, but the weapons were not fully operational until 1889, due to hydraulic system problems.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The barrel on the gun at Napier cracked during firing trials; this was because the crew had managed to stress the gun by firing one shot every 2.5 minutes.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The wrecked gun was not easily repairable so it was used as a foundation for a building.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The gun at Victoria Battery was moved to Napier, which the military deemed the more effective site.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The guns at Napier of Magdala Battery and at Fort Rinella are still intact and the installations are open to the public.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The guns were too costly to demolish and were left as junk, but both were later restored to display condition.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] Fort Rinella is under the guardianship of Fondazzjoni Wirt Artna - the Malta Heritage Trust.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/100-ton-gun] The pink paint on the Fort Rinella gun is a recent addition, originally they were unpainted.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The **18-pounder long gun** was an intermediary calibre piece of naval artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] They were used as main guns on the most typical frigates of the early 19th century, on the second deck of third-rate ships of the line, and even on the third deck of late first-rate ships of the line.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] As the 18-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, it was used in many European navies between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] It was a heavy calibre for early ships of the line, arming, for instance, the main batteries of *Couronne* in 1636.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] From the late 18th century, the French Navy used the 18-pounder in three capacities: as the main gun on frigates, as the battery on the upper gundeck of two-deckers, and lastly on the top deck of three-deckers.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] French frigates began carrying the 18-pounder under Louis XV, when the two *Pourvoyeuse*-class frigates, originally designed to carry 24-pounders, were equipped with it; at the time, a typical frigate would carry 12-pounders.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XVI, from 1779, the 18-pounder gradually became the standard calibre for frigates, starting with the *Hébé* class.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] These frigates were built on standard patterns designed by Jacques-Noël Sané, carrying 26, and later 28 main guns, complemented with smaller pieces on the forecastle.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Around 130 of these frigates were built.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] At the end of the First French Empire, 24-pounder frigates began supplanting the 18-pounder frigates.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Frigates built after the Bourbon Restoration used a different artillery system, one involving 30-pounders.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] On two-deckers, the 18-pounder was mounted on the upper deck as secondary artillery, to complement the 36-pounder main artillery on the lower deck.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] A 74-gun would carry thirty 18-pounders; this lighter secondary battery added firepower to the ship without raising the centre of gravity too much.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Three-deckers used 36-pounders on their lower decks and 24-pounders on their second deck.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] During the First French Empire, 18-pounders would also arm Type 1 Model Towers for coastal defence.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] After introduction of rifled artillery in the middle 19th century, long 18-pounders were converted into so-called "14 cm n° 1 rifled muzzle-loaders Model 1864", by etching grooves on the inside of the barrel.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] James mentions 6 different 18-pounder guns in the early 1720s.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 ft appears in a diagram from about 1735, where its weight was listed as 41 hundredweight 1 quarter 8 pounds.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The 1743 mensuration contains an 18-pounder of the same length and weight, with very similar dimensions.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] In tests in Minorca, one of the 18-pounders used was 9 ft long and weighed 39 hundredweight 1 quarter 3 pounds.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] 3 guns of 9 feet length from the reign of George II (1727–1760) currently survive at the Gut of Digby in Nova Scotia.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Their dimensions are similar to the gun in the 1735 diagram.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Adye's notebook from 1766 has an 18-pounder of 9 ft with almost identical dimensions to that in the 1735 diagram and 1743 mensuration.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The establishment of 1764 mentioned an 18-pounder gun of 9 ft and 40 hundredweight.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Walton included a gun with this length and weight in his table of dimensions in 1780, with similar dimensions to the 9 ft gun in the 1743 mensuration and the 1766 notebook.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Adye's manuals of 1801 and 1813 mention the 9 ft 40 hundredweight 18-pounder, though by then it was being superseded by the newer Blomefield guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9+1⁄2 ft is mentioned in Walton's table of dimensions in 1780, where its weight was 42 hundredweight.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] It also appears in Adye's manuals of 1801 and 1813, when it was also being superseded by Blomefield pattern guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 11 ft is first mentioned in tests in Minorca, where its weight was given as 51 hundredweight 5 pounds.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1820, 6 iron 18-pounders are mentioned, with weights from 50 to 54+1⁄4 hundredweight.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1857, an 18-pounder of 11 ft, "O.P" (old pattern) was in the list of guns submitted to the Committee on Ordnance.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 9 feet 42+1⁄2 hundredweight and 8 feet 37+3⁄4 hundredweight were widely used as siege and garrison guns in addition to their naval role.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] As a siege gun, the 18-pounder served the same role as the Canon de 16 Gribeauval.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 feet 42+1⁄2 hundredweight was used on the upper deck of 74-gun ships of the line.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 8 feet 37+3⁄4 hundredweight was used on the main deck of 46- and 42-gun frigates.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1825 Mould noted the gun of 6 feet 27 hundredweight was "not used at present." Although the guns of 6 feet 20 hundredweight and 5+1⁄2 feet 15 hundredweight were bored-up from Blomefield guns, an 1865 report mentions that they were designed by Alexander Dickson (Blomefield's successor).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] William Congreve designed an 18-pounder gun patterned after his 24-pounder gun, after the latter proved successful in trials in 1813.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] It was 6 feet 10 inches in length and 32 hundredweight.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] It had the same conical shape with more metal around the breech, and trunnions further to the rear.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] 8 pieces were mentioned in lists submitted to the Committee on Ordnance in 1857, though it may have only been experimental.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The guns retained were Blomefield or Dickson pattern guns mentioned above, as were the guns of 6 feet and 7 feet to be abolished.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 6 feet 10 inches was a Congreve gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 feet 40 hundredweight is not known, but it may have been the old 18-pounder of 9 feet from the establishment of 1764.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] The Royal Navy used the 18-pounder on frigates, which carried 28 guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Fourth-rate ships carried 26 on their secondary batteries, and third rates carried 28.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] Unlike the French, the British used second rates, of 90 to 98 guns; the 90-gun vessels carried thirty 18-pounders on their middle deck, while the 98-gun vessels carried a total of sixty 18-pounders, distributed over both the second and the third deck.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/18-pounder-long-gun] First rates carried thirty-four 18-pounders on their third deck and 24-pounders on the middle deck.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The **1897 pattern infantry officers' sword** is a straight-bladed, three-quarter basket-hilted sword that has been the regulation sword for officers of the line infantry of the British Army from 1897 to the present day.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The curved, Gothic-hilted 1822 and 1845 pattern infantry swords, although elegant, had been criticised by some as fighting swords.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] In common with British cavalry swords of the era, they were cut-and-thrust swords.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] In 1892, a new, straight, blade was introduced, mated to the existing Gothic hilt.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] Presaging the introduction of the 1908 pattern cavalry sword, the curved blade was abandoned in favour of a straight, stiff blade optimised for the thrust.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] Credit for the design has been given to Colonel G.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] Fox, Inspector of Gymnasia at Aldershot, who was also influential in the design of the pattern 1908 cavalry sword.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] In 1895, a new pierced steel hilt pattern was introduced, replacing the earlier Gothic hilt with a three-quarter basket hilt.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The new pattern was short-lived due to the edge of the guard fraying uniforms, and in 1897 the final pattern was settled on, being simply the 1895 pattern with the inner edge of the guard turned down, and the piercings becoming smaller.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] By the time of its introduction, the sword was of limited use on the battlefield against rapid-firing rifles, machine guns and long-range artillery.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] However, the new sword was regarded, when needed, as a very effective fighting weapon.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] Reports from the Sudan, where it was used in close-quarters fighting during the reconquest of the Sudan (1896–1899) were positive.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] Officers carried swords into battle in 1914 at the start of the First World War, and some were still being used in action at the Battle of Neuve Chapelle in March 1915.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] Bernard Montgomery advanced with his 1897 pattern sword drawn during a counteroffensive in October 1914; having never received any training on how to use it.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The actual sword he carried is exhibited in the Imperial War Museum, London.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The design of the 1897 pattern has remained unchanged to the present day, and is now manufactured by various companies, including Weyersberg, Kirschbaum & Cie of Germany and Pooley Sword of the UK.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] Until 2004, swords of this pattern would be used in courts-martial by escorts of the accused and if the accused was an officer, he would lay his sword on the table for judgement.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The blade is described in the pattern as being 32+1⁄2 inches (830 mm) long and 1 inch (25 mm) wide at the shoulder, with the complete sword weighing between 1 pound 12 ounces (0.79 kg) and 1 pound 13 ounces (0.82 kg).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The blade is straight and appears symmetrical in shape (though in cross-section is a wedge, with the edge towards the front).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The thick blade has a deep central fuller on each side and is rounded on both its edge and back towards the hilt, giving a “dumbbell” or “girder” cross section.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] Through a gradual transition, the blade becomes a wedge-section with the main cutting edge towards the front.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The last 13 inches (330 mm) of the front edge was sharpened when on active service (and a few inches of the false edge, at the back near the tip, to aid penetration).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The blade ends in a sharp stiff spear point.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The blade is usually decoratively etched on both sides.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The guard is a three-quarter basket of sheet steel.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] It is decorated with a pierced scroll-work pattern and (usually, see variation, below) has the royal cypher of the reigning monarch set over the lower knuckle bow.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The grip, between 5 and 5+3⁄4 inches (130 and 150 mm) long to suit the hand of the owner, is generally covered in ray or sharkskin and wrapped with German-silver wire.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The grip is straight, with no offset to the blade.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The sword shows a number of features that indicate its intent as a thrusting weapon.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The stiff tapering narrow point aids penetration.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The blade, whilst quite narrow, is thick and its dumbbell section gives it good weak-axis buckling strength whilst maintaining robustness in bending for the parry.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The blade tapers in both width and thickness and, with the substantial guard, has a hilt-biased balance, aiding agility at the expense of concussive force in a cut.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The guard gives comprehensive protection to the hand, but does not restrict wrist movement.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The length of the front edge, at 17 inches (430 mm), is quite significant, suggesting that some cutting capability was maintained, even if the blade design is clearly intended as a thruster.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] In common with earlier patterns, the 1897 pattern was sometime produced in "picquet" weight, i.e., a lighter weapon with a narrower blade and correspondingly scaled-down guard for use in levées and other formal occasions when not on active service.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] Some regiments carried variations on the standard pattern, generally consisting of variations of the royal cypher on the guard.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] An unetched blade variant is available for warrant officers.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/1897-pattern-british-infantry-officer-s-sword] The sword pattern also influenced the ceremonial sword used by the Hong Kong Police Force's Ceremonial uniform as well as the 1897 Canadian Infantry Sword used by the Canadian Army.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The **24-pounder long gun** was a heavy calibre piece of artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] 24-pounders were in service in the navies of France, Spain, Great Britain, the Netherlands, Sweden, and the United States.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] They were comparable to the Canon de 24 Gribeauval used by the French Army as its largest piece of siege artillery.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] 24-pounders were used as main guns on the heaviest frigates of the early 19th century and on fourth-rate ships of the line, on the second deck of first-rate ships of the line, and on the second deck of a few large third-rates.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The 24-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, and was a widespread gun amongst nations between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] From the late 18th century, the French Navy used the 24-pounder in two capacities: as main gun on frigates and 64-guns, or as secondary artillery on three-deckers and even enlarged versions two-deckers.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The experiment was tried again in 1785 with *Pomone*, a successful design that opened the way to a standardisation on the 24-pounder frigate exemplified by the *Romaine* class.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Overall, 14 of these heavy frigates were built between *Pomone* in 1785, and *Poursuivante* in 1798, each carrying between 24 and 30 24-pounders.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] After the Bourbon Restoration, frigates were built using a different artillery system, carrying 30-pounders.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Two-deckers used the 24-pounder in two capacities: on the smallest two-deckers of 64 guns, the 24-pounder constituted the main artillery, with 26 pieces.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Typical 74-gun vessels carried a 36-pounder main battery and an 18-pounder secondary battery, until the enlarged variant of the *Téméraire* class appeared in 1803, comprising *Vétéran* and *Cassard*.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] More significantly, the 24-pounder armed the secondary battery of all 80-gun ships of the line from 1749, when the *Soleil-Royal* introduced the practice, resulting in a two-decker with enough firepower to challenge a three-decker of the time.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] During the reign of Louis XIV, three-deckers were standardised on a 36-pounder main artillery and an 18-pounder secondary battery.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] From the mid-18th century, under Louis XV, the secondary battery was strengthened to 24-pounders, beginning with the *Sans-Pareil* design that yielded *Royal Louis*.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The other capital ships of the era, *Ville de Paris*, flagship of François Joseph Paul de Grasse during the American War of Independence, and *Bretagne*, flagship at the Battle of Ushant, similarly carried 24-pounders as secondary batteries.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The practices was continued with the *Océan* class and the *Commerce de Paris* class.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] During the First French Empire, 24-pounders would also arm Type 1 Model Towers for coastal defence.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] In the Royal Navy, the 24-pounder was similarly used on some heavy frigates, which carried 26 guns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Fourth-rate ships carried 22 on their secondary batteries, and third-rates carried 32.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] First-rates carried thirty-four 24-pounders on their middle deck.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Ten surviving guns which are likely examples of the 91⁄2-foot version weigh between 48 and 493⁄4 hundredweight.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] These guns are very similar to the gun of 91⁄2 feet and 491⁄4 hundredweight which was detailed in the mensuration of 1743.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] One other 24-pounder is mentioned in sources from 1780 and later, specifically a gun of 10 feet and 52 hundredweight.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] It is unknown whether the gun was new or the same as the 10 foot 24-pounder mentioned above.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Except the guns of 501⁄2, 473⁄4, 22, and 20 hundredweight, most of these guns were little used, and declared obsolete in 1865 by the War Department.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns cast in 1813 were designed to be evaluated against William Congreve's new pattern of gun.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 91⁄2 feet 501⁄2 hundredweight and 9 feet 473⁄4 hundredweight were highly regarded as siege guns and widely used in that role in addition to their naval use.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 22 and 20 hundredweight were mostly used in casemates and flank defenses as replacements for 24-pounder carronades.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] In response to a desire for lighter 24-pounders that could still be double-shotted,William Congreve designed a radical new type of 24-pounder, which was shorter, lighter, and with more metal concentrated around the gun breech rather than the chase (gun barrel).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] It had a muzzle similar to a carronade, and the breeching ring was discarded in favor of a hole in the center of the neck of the cascabel.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Because the weight of the cannon was much farther back, the trunnions could also be cast much farther rearward than in a similar conventional cannon.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The heavier gun was tested in HMS *Eurotas* in October 1813, and the lighter gun was tested on HMS *Pactolus* in February 1814.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] The results were so favorable (despite somewhat violent recoil) that 300 more guns were ordered, and by 1820, Congreve noted 700 guns as being cast.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Congreve also suggested several other guns to be constructed according to his principle, including a 24-pounder of 8 feet and 50 hundredweight.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] However, the recoil of the guns when in service proved to be worse than the trials indicated, and they were withdrawn from service by 1830, except in East India Company service.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] That year, 800 24-pounders were bored-up to produce 32-pounders, and they remained in active service in that role past 1865.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Congreve's other suggested guns were never used beyond the testing stage.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] These were similar to the Blomefield designs, but with a slightly smaller caliber of 5.792 instead of 5.823 inches.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] In addition, a number of guns designated "N.P." for New Pattern appear in the records of the Committee on Ordnance.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Finally, a 24-pounder of either 4 ft 10 in (1.47 m) or 5 ft (1.5 m) and 18 cwt was mentioned, and it was declared obsolete in 1865 by the War Department.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Images are available showing 24-pounder long guns as the main gun deck armament on the USS *Independence* as used during the American Revolution; and the USS *Constitution* and USS *Constellation* as two of the original six frigates of the United States Navy starting in 1797.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] From the War of 1812 until the 1840s, The U.S.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] Navy used three classifications: the gun proper, which had a barrel weight of 150 lb (68 kg) per pound of shot, the double-fortified gun which had a barrel weight of 200 lb (91 kg) per pound of shot, and the medium gun, which had a barrel weight of 100 lb (45 kg) per pound of shot.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/24-pounder-long-gun] By comparison, a carronade would have a barrel weight of 65 lb (29 kg) per pound of shot.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] A **muzzle-loading rifle** is a muzzle-loaded small arm that has a rifled barrel rather than a smoothbore, and is loaded from the muzzle of the barrel rather than the breech.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Historically they were developed when rifled barrels were introduced by the 1740's, which offered higher accuracy than the earlier smoothbores.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The American longrifle evolved from the German "Jäger" rifle; a popularly recognizable form of the "muzzleloader" was the Kentucky Rifle.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Although by definition they must be reloaded after each shot in a time-consuming fashion, they are still produced for hunting.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Comparable artillery pieces are termed rifled muzzle loader (RML).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Like most early firearms, the first rifles were muzzle-loading, although this involved a lot of complication in inserting the bullet past the rifling, and clogging and cleaning problems were notorious.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] There are also muzzle-loading pistols and shotguns.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The Minié ball of the middle 19th century increased the rate of fire of rifles to match that of smoothbores, and rifled muzzle-loading small arms were rapidly adopted.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] These long rifles and similar weapons were used from about 1700 to 1900, but gradually gave way to firearms whose projectile is loaded into the chamber via the breech, without having to pass through the barrel.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] equipped with lugs which allowed it to follow the rifle grooves inside the cannon bore.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The La Hitte rifled guns were used from 1859 during the Franco-Austrian War in Italy.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] These guns were a considerable improvement over the previous smooth-bore guns which had been in use.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] They were able to shoot at 3,000 meters either regular shells, ball-loaded shells or grapeshot.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] They appear to have been the first case of usage of rifled cannons on a battlefield.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The muzzle-loading rifle was introduced into service in ships of the Royal Navy, after experimentation with alternative armament systems, after the failure of the Armstrong 100-pounder breech-loaders installed in 1860.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Until the middle of the 19th century Royal Navy warships had been armed with progressively larger smoothbore muzzle-loading cannon.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] These had by then approached their limit in terms of armour penetration, range and destructive power.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] It was known that rifled ordnance provided more accuracy, a greater range and more penetrative power, which was the rationale behind the development and on-board shipping of the breech-loading cannon developed by the company owned by Sir William Armstrong.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] These weapons, however, were dangerously prone to failure, frequently explosively, and an alternative armament became urgently necessary.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] An initial attempt at an alternative was the 100-pounder smoothbore Somerset cannon, which, while it was an improvement over previous smoothbore guns of lesser calibre, could not penetrate armour of thicknesses currently being shipped by British or foreign battleships.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The type of gun finally adopted was a muzzle-loading weapon which fired projectiles with external studs which engaged with the rifling.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] This system was the "Woolwich" system; while it was possible with this system to fire shells at a higher muzzle velocity, and therefore with greater penetrative power, than before, the studs tended to shear, there was excessive wear of the gun liner, and the shells tended to wobble in flight.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Furthermore, the muzzle velocity obtainable in these guns was no more than half of that obtained in interrupted screw breeched guns of the following century.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Rifled muzzle loader (RMLs) are artillery pieces of muzzle-loading rifle format, invented in the mid-19th century.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] In contrast to smooth bore cannon which preceded it, the rifling of the gun barrel allowed much greater accuracy and penetration as the spin induced to the shell gave it directional stability.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Typical guns weighed 30 tonnes with 10" diameter muzzles, and were installed in forts and ships.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] This new gun and the rifled breech loader generated a huge arms race in the late 19th century, with rapid advances in fortifications and ironclad warships.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] In the British navy, many smaller 64-pounder smoothbore guns were converted to rifled weapons: the converted guns were called RMLs, whilst weapons manufactured with rifling were termed muzzle-loading rifles.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] This distinction did not survive with the larger calibres, which were generally all called RMLs.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Many artillery pieces were converted from older smooth bore weapons once technical problems in strengthening the original cast iron body had been overcome.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The widely adopted solution, invented in 1863 by William Palliser, consisted of enlarging the bore to accept a wrought iron tube (called the *A tube*) into which the rifling had been cut.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The A tube was closed at the breech end by a wrought iron cup screwed into it.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Iron was removed from the outside of the original gun barrel near to the muzzle so that a cast iron collar could be screwed over it and provide a shoulder at the muzzle to hold the A tube in place.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The A tube was also held by a plug screwed into the gun underneath its trunnions.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The outside of the breech portion was turned on a lathe so that another wrought iron tube, called the *B tube*, could be slid over it to strengthen it.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The largest RML carried on a warship was the Elswick Ordnance Company's 17.7 inch (450-mm) 100 ton gun of the 1870s, four of which were installed in each of the Italian ironclads *Duilio* and *Enrico Dandolo* (launched in 1876 and 1878, respectively).
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The Royal Navy at the time was restricted to the weapons produced by Woolwich Arsenal, so that the heaviest guns that could be shipped were the 80 ton 16 inch guns of HMS *Inflexible*.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] During this period rapid burning black powder was used as the propellant, so the guns had a stubby, 'soda bottle' shape giving easy access to either end for loading.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] The RBLs of the time were notably weaker in the breech region, and more prone to failure.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Improvements in breech mechanisms in the period 1860 to 1880, together with the introduction of large grain powder, caused the Navy to re-adopt the RBL as the new powder required longer barrels which could not be withdrawn into the turret for loading.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] A new 12-inch gun was developed for HMS *Edinburgh* in 1879, but burst during trials.
[src:muzzle-loading-rifle/muzzle-loading-rifle] Following modifications the new weapon proved reliable.
